elements.title: Mawali
elements.contents: ... that in the 18th century the Mawali tribe (pictured) was driven from the Syrian steppe to the regions of Hama and Idlib, where their descendants live today?

elements.title: Ceechynaa
elements.contents: ... that a reviewer identified an "audible contempt" for men in the songs of Ceechynaa, who entered the UK singles chart earlier this month with "Peggy"?

elements.title: vitamin E
elements.contents: ... that vitamin E was named "tocopherol" as it was identified as essential for live births in rats?

elements.title: puff-puff
elements.contents: ... that the sexual onomatopoeia puff-puff was censored in English releases of Dragon Quest until Dragon Quest XI?

elements.title: Jacob Frolich
elements.contents: ... that newspaper publisher Jacob Frolich built trapdoors and hiding places in his house in case it was raided by Radical Republicans?

elements.title: Chernobyl Reactors 5 and 6
elements.contents: ... that nearly 300 construction workers showed up at 8 am to continue building Chernobyl Reactors 5 and 6, unaware of the Chernobyl disaster earlier that day?

elements.title: Bernard Gray
elements.contents: ... that war correspondent Bernard Gray was killed while travelling as an unofficial passenger aboard a Royal Navy submarine during the Second World War?

elements.title: Good Gravy!
elements.contents: ... that Good Gravy!, a Thanksgiving dinner–themed roller coaster, was first tested with a train full of plush turkeys?
